**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** It works just like any other unmanaged type with `stackalloc`. Here on this 64-bit system each element is 8 bytes; on a 32-bit runtime it would be 4 bytes.

```csharp
Span<nint> nints = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> nuints = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

Both `nint` and `nuint` satisfy the `unmanaged` constraint required by `stackalloc`, so this has been supported since C# 9 (when `nint`/`nuint` were introduced) combined with `Span<T>` stackalloc (C# 7.2+).
